const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What's the most common Whirlpool washer problem?",
    a: "Two most common, depending on which Whirlpool washer family you have. On Cabrio top-load washers (WTW-series), the lid lock / lid switch is the #1 service item, typical year 3-6 failure window, presents as the washer not starting, not entering spin, or stopping mid-cycle even though the lid appears closed. Replacement runs $145-$215. On Duet front-load washers (WFW-series), the drain pump is the most common service call, debris (coins, hair, lint) and wear lead to drain failures and F02 / F21 long-drain error codes year 5-8. Pump replacement $245-$385. Across both families, control panel responsiveness issues climb starting around year 7-9, Whirlpool washers have a documented pattern of touch-panel and keypad failures that's worth knowing about before repair-vs-replace decisions on older units."
  },
  {
    q: "What does an F01 / F02 / F11 / F26 error code mean on my Whirlpool washer?",
    a: "F01, main control board (CCU) communication or internal fault. Reset by unplugging for 10 minutes; if F01 returns, the CCU needs replacement ($345-$525). F02, long drain error; the control didn't detect drain completion within 8 minutes. Drain pump, drain hose, or drain filter clog is the cause; pump or filter clean $145-$385. F11, serial communication error between the CCU (main board) and MCU (motor control unit). Less commonly a wiring harness issue between the two boards; more commonly one of the boards has failed. Diagnostic separates which. F26, door or lid switch error. The control didn't detect the door opening after 3 consecutive loads, suggesting a loose wire at the door lock or PCB, or a defective lid lock assembly. About 70% of F26 codes resolve at lid lock replacement on Cabrio or door lock replacement on Duet."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between Whirlpool Cabrio and Duet washers?",
    a: "Two different architectures. Cabrio is Whirlpool's high-efficiency top-load family, most are impeller-driven (no agitator), with electronic controls and a glass lid. WTW-series model numbers. Service tree: lid lock (year 3-6), drain pump (year 6-9), drive belt and shift actuator (year 5-8), suspension rod kit (year 9+ for unbalanced-load issues), main control board year 8-12. Duet is the front-load family, WFW-series. Service tree: drain pump (year 5-8), door boot (year 8-10, tearing or mold ingress), bearing + drum seal year 8-12 (replaced as a set; replacing only the bearing without the seal fails again within months), main control board (CCU). Both families share Whirlpool engineering platform with Maytag, many Maytag washers are mechanically identical to Whirlpool variants with cosmetic trim differences. Same parts network on our trucks."
  },
  {
    q: "Why does my Whirlpool washer keep stopping mid-cycle?",
    a: "Three common causes, in diagnostic order. (1) Lid lock fault (Cabrio top-load) or door lock fault (Duet front-load), washer believes door has opened and stops the cycle for safety. F26 error code if displayed; sometimes silent. About 50% of mid-cycle stoppage. (2) Drain pump issue, washer can't drain fully and stalls before spin. F02 error code typically shown. About 30% of cases. (3) Unbalanced load detection, washer enters extended re-balance attempts and times out. About 15% of cases. The remaining 5% is various, failing CCU, water inlet valve issue, thermistor drift. Diagnostic order: visual lid lock check, drain pump filter clean, redistribute load. About 30% resolve at the homeowner-troubleshooting layer at no parts cost."
  },
  {
    q: "What does Sud / Sd error mean on my Whirlpool washer?",
    a: "Sud or Sd means \"excess suds detected\", the washer is reading too much foam in the drum and pausing the cycle to let it dissipate. Two causes: (1) wrong detergent (regular detergent in an HE machine generates substantially more suds than HE detergent does), or (2) too much HE detergent (HE detergents are concentrated; standard \"fill the cap\" dosing is usually too much for HE machines). Switching to HE detergent and reducing the dose to 1-2 tablespoons per regular load resolves the vast majority of Sud / Sd codes at no service cost. If Sud persists with correct HE detergent at correct dose, the diagnostic is the pressure sensor or the drain pump, but those are uncommon causes of Sud specifically."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does Whirlpool washer repair cost in LA?",
    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when work is approved. Common Whirlpool washer repairs: lid switch / lid lock (Cabrio top-load) $145-$215; drain pump $245-$385; water inlet valve $185-$285; drive belt + shift actuator (Cabrio) $185-$345; suspension rod kit (Cabrio year 9+) $245-$385; door boot (Duet front-load) $285-$425; bearing + drum seal (Duet year 8-12) $585-$880; control panel / keypad assembly $285-$445; main control board (CCU) $345-$525; F11 CCU+MCU diagnostic and replacement $345-$680 depending on which board failed. Maytag-branded units share platform with Whirlpool and run the same pricing. KitchenAid washers (KAWE series) run 15-25% above base Whirlpool because of premium-tier component spec."
  },
  {
    q: "Are Whirlpool washers worth repairing or should I replace?",
    a: "Honest framework. Under year 6: repair almost always, Whirlpool washers should run reliably to year 12-15 with normal maintenance. Year 6-10 with typical lid-lock / drain pump / control panel work, repair makes sense for any quote under $400, that covers most Whirlpool service calls. Year 10-12 with major repair (CCU + MCU on a Duet, suspension rod + control panel on a Cabrio): repair-vs-replace tilts toward replacement on entry-tier WTW2 / WFW3 models. Year 12+: replacement usually wins unless your unit is a high-spec WFW9620 or WTW8500 where replacement cost is substantial enough to justify major repair. The 50% rule of thumb: if the repair quote exceeds 50% of replacement cost AND the unit is over 10 years old, replacement usually wins. We tell you the math on the diagnostic visit."
  }
];

